                                  "PostMention": "."
                               }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "introduction",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Introduction\n\nIn the previous text, we explored an axiom stating that any value added to zero (0) equals itself (Additive Identity). Additionally, we learned that advancing a number in the numerical sequence is equivalent to adding one (1) to the previous number",
                                 "source" : [
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "7a9c733b-ca13-40f5-8849-19012540b028",
                                                "text": "Ernst, Dana.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "6e3666ca-88e4-4b5e-a717-c42056476a77",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Team",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2025", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On axioms</b><br /><br />If an axiom exists for adding zero, could there also be axioms for adding other numbers?</div></div></center></p>",
                               { "text" : "In this text, we will delve deeper into addition and explore how we can move more efficiently along the numerical axis",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "axiom",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### The Addition Order\n\nThe addition operation has a fundamental property, which is also an axiom. While we have not yet fully explored it, this property will be essential in guiding our studies. Let’s revisit the representation of a numerical axis",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                                "<p><div class=\"chart\"><div class=\"tick\"><span>0</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>1</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>2</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>3</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>4</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>5</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>6</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>7</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>8</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>9</span></div><div class=\"tick arrow rightarrow\"></div></div></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"desc\">Graph 1: Representation of an axis with numbers. The numbers are placed below the line, and an arrow on the right end indicates the direction in which the values increase. The source code used to generate the CSS-based image is available on <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('c7edc93c-0a41-4753-8f89-9e52904ff003'); return false;\">W3 Schools</a>.</p>",
                               { "text" : "Based on what we have learned previously, let’s begin by working with the number 5. On the axis shown above, we can interpret a person standing on the number 5 as being five units to the right of the origin. This means the person has taken five steps from zero (0). Additionally, we know that adding zero (0) to any number leaves the number unchanged. For example",
                                 "source" : [
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "6e3666ca-88e4-4b5e-a717-c42056476a77",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Team",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2025", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>5</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>0</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> </math></p>",
                               "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i><b>Calculation 1:</b> Adding zero (0) and five (5).</i></li></ul></p>",
                               "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: On Inversion</b><br /><br />Would the result be the same if, instead of calculating <b>5 + 0</b>, we calculated <b>0 + 5</b>?</div></div></center></p>",
                               { "text" : "From the axiom we learned earlier, we know that adding zero to any number results in the same number. Therefore, both **0 + 5** and **5 + 0**, yield the same result, as we are simply adding zero (0) to the number 5 in both cases.\n\nThis principle applies to other numbers as well. For example, if we add four (4) and one (1), and then reverse the order by adding one (1) and four (4), the result remains the same",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>4</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> </math></p>",
                               "<p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>4</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> </math></p>",
                               "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i><b>Calculation 2:</b> Adition of integer numbers.</i></li></ul></p>",
                               { "text" : "We can visualize these calculations using the numerical axis in **Chart 1**. In the first case, we start at position four (4) and advance one (1) step to reach position five (5). In the second case, we start at position one (1) and advance four (4) steps, again reaching position five (5).\n\nBased on these observations, we can define the **Commutative Axiom**",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i><b>Commutative Axiom:</b> For any numbers <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>, the order of addition does not change the result:<br /> a + b = b + a</i></li></ul></p>",
                               { "text" : "To conclude this section, let’s apply the Commutative Axiom to Calculation 2",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>4</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> +  <mn>4</mn> </math></p>"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "growing",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Addition as Reconstructions\n\nHuman constructions often involve a form of numerical addition. A notable example is **Temple 16 in Copán**, which underwent multiple reconstruction phases and now stands over 30 meters tall. In its earliest stages, however, the temple was significantly smaller",
                                 "source" : [
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "daae87a2-5fa9-43d1-88fb-6713b25d50d5",
                                                "text": "Tuarez Mejia, L. F.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2023", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Temple16Copan.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: Sign at the Archaeological Site of Copán (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>). Photo taken on <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
                               { "text" : "The Mesoamerican reconstruction process typically occurred in successive stages with minimal gaps between them. However, **Temple 16** presents an exception: the reconstruction that followed the *Rosalila* phase left an intermediate space, allowing visitors to walk through these areas, as shown in **Figure 2**",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple2', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Templo16Inside.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width:40%;\"/>Figure 2: Internal view of Temple 16 in Copán  (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>). Photo taken on <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
                               { "text" : "The process of numerical addition can be likened to these Indigenous reconstructions. When performing addition, we always begin with the smallest value and progress to the largest. Furthermore, based on the two axioms we have already explored, we can conclude that addition always occurs in pairs of numbers, represented in the axioms as *a* and *b*, until the final result is achieved.\n\nIn the next subsection, we will explore the details of calculating large numbers",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "exercise_v2",
                    "text" : [ 
                        {
                            "question" : "Se eu somar <b>5 + 4</b>, terei um resultado diferente de somar <b>4 + 5</b>?",
                            "yesNoAnswer" : "No",
                            "additionalInfo" : "Como mencionado no <b>Axioma da Comutatividade</b>, a ordem que somamos um número, não altera o resultado."
                        }
                    ]
